Thank you Miranda Martinez for this great post on your Facebook page:
My Tatum has been having a hard time with school this year. Every morning he is upset and just wants to stay home. I notified the school, never having dealt with this before. The staff at LAES has gone above and beyond to help. Mrs. Gardner has been waiting the last two mornings to walk with him into school. This has helped tremendously. More than she probably knows. All of the elementary staff is so kind and have smiles on their faces every morning. His teacher, Mrs. Laurent, let‚Äôs me bother her all day long. Mrs. Montez, trying her hardest and having so much patience at drop off. This and many other reasons are why my children go to school at LAES! We appreciate ALL of you! Thank you isn‚Äôt enough! üíôü§ç #TrojanPride

post_text:
OPEN FOR BUSINESS

Just a reminder that Boggsville and the Museum are open for business with usual restrictions ‚Äì masks and social distancing. We would love to have you visit. Boggsville is open Tuesday ‚Äì Saturday, from 11am to 4pm through September. Museum hours are Tuesday 9am ‚Äì 4pm; Wednesday thru Saturday noon-4pm. We are CLOSED SUNDAY AND MONDAY, but available for private tours by appointment. Our 41st Bent County Chronicle has been sent to the printers so that should be coming soon to members. Come and see how the volunteers continue to improve our exhibits. Our latest enhancements are children mannequins, which are so special; Native American exhibit additions; and our World War II exhibit. You can always come on Tuesdays and look for Bent County roots in the Heritage Library. Call 456-6066 with any questions.

Sessions are also recorded if you can't watch them live! Colorado Kids are invited to the 2020 Virtual State Fair Day Camp
The Colorado State Fair is calling all kids to head to the 2020 State Fair Day Camp--from the safety of their own homes. The virtual, first-ever State Fair camp will be held on four afternoons from Monday, August 31 through Thursday, September 3, beginning at 3:30 p.m. each day.

The program is designed for students in grades 3-5, and younger children are welcome to participate with older family members.

post_text:
I wanted to share this great message that was sent to our Facebook Page.....what a wonderful project Grace did with her card drive! #trojanpride

Hello. I'm from Beloit Wisconsin. I was in the hospital for surgery. The nurse came in and said I have mail. Lol. At first I thought my bill collectors were working overtime but to my surprise I got a get well card from a Grace Gardner. I was blown away. I'm in bed in pain from surgery and I get a card from someone I have never met and chances are never will. THANK YOU VERY MUCH Grace. You made my day. With all the junk you see on tv it was awesome to get something like this. Your parents and teachers did a great job. I understand from doing some research that the school did this as a group. You young people will most definitely put a smile on alot of people on what could be a crummy day. From the bottom of my heart Grace and to the school. Thank you very much.
Sincerely
Randy Meier.
From
Beloit Wisconsin.....

shared_text:
Bent's Old Fort National Historic Site
June 26 at 3:43 PM ¬∑

Today at the Fort:

One of the common questions visitors ask is "Do you actually use the wagons?" The answer is yes! Our oxen are used to pull each of our vehicles. Just like a car today, maintenance was important to keep the freight rolling along the Santa Fe Trail. You can see in the photograph that two Bent, St. Vrain, & Co. Employees are busy removing the wheels to make sure there is a proper amount of grease.

The green Conestoga will be leading our parade from the parking lot to the fort to kickoff our July 4th festivities!

#FindYourPark

(NPS Photo of two Rangers in period clothing applying grease to a wagon.)

Bent County Development Foundation
June 15 at 7:20 PM ¬∑

As of 6/15 the Bent County Business Relief Fund will be accepting applications for funding on a rolling basis. This means that your business/organization can submit an application at any point for consideration until funds are expended.

This funding is available to any business located within Bent County. Funding can be used to cover or reimburse for expenses incurred starting April 1, 2020.

Even if you've already applied and even if you've already received funding you're eligible to apply again- you will simply need to provide NEW bills for reimbursement.

Please apply for funding by visiting the following link:
https://forms.gle/y4N2P3LMgbCMJPuP8

June 15 at 7:20 PM ¬∑

As of 6/15 the Bent County Business Relief Fund will be accepting applications for funding on a rolling basis. This means that your business/organization can submit an application at any point for consideration until funds are expended.

Even if you've already applied and even if you've already received funding you're eligible to apply again- you will simply need to provide NEW bills for reimbursement.

post_text:
Museum Honors WWII Veterans
By Kathleen Tomlin

September 2, 2020 will mark the 75th Commemoration of the End of World War II; a war that took the lives of over 405,000 U.S. military personnel. The ‚ÄúMighty Mo,‚Äù which now rests on the hallowed waters of Pearl Harbor, is a reminder of those who gave the ultimate sacrifice in restoring peace to the world. Even though the Museum is not yet open to the public because of the pandemic, volunteers have been busy doing various things to prepare for the opening. In honor of World War II (1939 ‚Äì 1945) they decided to honor the men and women of World War II with a window display for the summer. We hope you enjoy it. We are being told that we can probably open very soon. We have missed our patrons and cannot wait to see you again. Call 456-6066 with any questions.

post_text:
CIVIC CLUB SHARING by Kathleen Tomlin

The Woman‚Äôs Civic Club held their last luncheon meeting for the year at the Rawlings Heritage Center this past Saturday. Due to the COVID pandemic, they were not able to have as many fund-raising activities this year but were proud to raise over $1,000 on the quilt give-away. Diane Baublits was thrilled to win the quilt drawing and stated she has made many quilts but has never ‚Äúwon‚Äù a quilt. The Club spent the meeting distributing over $2000 funds to local groups that can use a helping hand. New officers were elected beginning in September, and they are Donna Martenson, President; Adele McAfee, Vice-President; Tammy Pryor, Secretary; and Kathleen Tomlin, Treasurer. We would like to thank the Community for their generous support of our activities!

Las Animas School District Superintendent, Elsie Goines and a number of other rural superintendents crafted a letter to send to the Denver Post and our local newspapers to emphasize the differences for Rural Colorado and the rest of the state concerning COVID. As you know, many large districts are dictating COVID measures that are then being applied to rural areas across Colorado. We are asking leaders to take time to consider the differences as they relate to the number of cases and such.

--

The Academic Excellence Awards program recognizes those students Grades 7 through 12 who have maintained a 3.5 Grade Point Average for the 1st three quarters of the academic school year.

If any Senior student has qualified for the Academic Excellence award throughout their entire school career (from Grades 7 thru 12) they are additionally awarded the "Senior Award".

Additionally, those Academic Excellence recipients who have completed and are considered in good standing in at least 3 sports are awarded an Academic Excellence Athlete distinction.

This year didn't finish up how anyone thought it would, at SHG, we want to recognize the huge milestone you have reached in graduating high school.
